Taiwan Stocks: Formosa Plastics, Nanya, Powerchip, Tung Ho Steel

-- B y   W e i y i   L i m
-- 
2011-03-14T06:10:24Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-14/taiwan-stocks-formosa-plastics-nanya-powerchip-tung-ho-steel.html
Stocks of the following companies
had unusual moves in Taiwan trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of 1:30 p.m. close.  The Taiex Index fell 47.80, or 0.6 percent, to 8,520.02.  Automobile: Yulon Motor Co. (2201 TT) slumped 6.8 percent
to NT$54.50, the biggest drop since Feb. 5, 2010.  China Motor
Corp. (2204)  (2204 TT) slid 7 percent to NT$23.25, the most since July
16, 1999. Hotai Motor Co. (2207 TT) lost 4.4 percent to NT$83.  There’s speculation a shortage of supplies from autopart
makers in  Japan  after an earthquake will curb shipments, said
Eric Chen, an analyst at Polaris Securities Co. Hotai said in a
statement to the Taiwan Stock Exchange Toyota Motor Corp. will
halt all production facilities in Japan from March 14 to 16 for
inspection after the March 11 earthquake. China Motor said in a
statement to the bourse the quake didn’t have any major impact
on the business. Shiao Ming-Huei, Yulon spokesman didn’t answer
calls to his office.  Chipmakers:  Powerchip Technology Corp. (5346)  (5346 TT) climbed 7
percent to NT$6.45, the biggest jump since July 28.  Nanya
Technology Corp. (2408)  (2408 TT) advanced 2.6 percent to NT$15.90 and  Inotera Memories Inc. (3474)  (3474 TT) added 4.5 percent to NT$15.  Powerchip has halted pricing for its spot memory chips as
it is assessing Japanese wafer supply after an earthquake, Eric Tang, company spokesman, said by phone today.  Petrochemicals: Formasa Plastics Corp. (1301 TT) surged 5.8
percent to NT$98.20, the most since May 4, 2009.  Formosa
Petrochemical Corp. (6505)  (6505 TT) jumped 6.6 percent to NT$93.40.  Formosa Chemicals & Fibre Corp. (1326)  (1326 TT) climbed 5.2 percent to
NT$104. Investors predict increased demand for the companies’
products after Japan’s earthquake, said Danny Ho, an analyst at
Yuanta Securities Co.  Formosa Plastics halted April export price quotes for
petrochemical products after the earthquake, as production
conditions at its Japanese competitors are “unclear,” Jerry Lin, a company spokesman, said by phone in Taipei today.
Taiwan’s petrochemical companies have suspended pricing for
April export orders after the earthquake, the Apple Daily
reported, citing unidentified people in the industry.  Steelmakers:  Tung Ho Steel Enterprise Corp. (2006)  (2006 TT)
surged 6.8 percent to NT$32.80, the biggest advance since Nov.
10.  Feng Hsin Iron & Steel Co. (2015)  (2015 TT) jumped 6.7 percent to
NT$52.90, the most since Sept. 7.  China Steel Corp. (2002)  (2002 TT)
gained 2.8 percent to NT$34.35. Taiwan companies may benefit
from increased orders due to shortages caused by Japan’s
earthquake, said Marc Wang, an analyst at KGI Securities Co.  To contact the reporter on this story:
